WEBVTT

00:02.131 --> 00:04.281
Everyone thinks they know the man,

00:04.282 --> 00:05.779
but nobody knows Lincoln.

00:05.922 --> 00:07.151
He was a wrestler, for one.

00:07.152 --> 00:09.021
300 fights, only lost once.

00:09.056 --> 00:10.333
What do you know about Lincoln?

00:10.357 --> 00:11.624
I'm his bodyguard.

00:11.658 --> 00:13.092
Why aren't you guarding him, then?

00:13.126 --> 00:15.027
He's next door, watching the play.

00:15.062 --> 00:17.396
Hey, Mr. Booth.

00:17.431 --> 00:18.898
Wife's been asking

00:18.932 --> 00:21.333
when we're gonna be
seeing you on stage again.

00:23.170 --> 00:24.904
Soon.

00:24.938 --> 00:27.907
<i>[suspenseful dramatic music]</i>

00:27.941 --> 00:34.947
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:36.616 --> 00:37.917
[muffled play dialogue]

00:37.951 --> 00:40.152
<i>You crave affection. You do.</i>

00:40.187 --> 00:42.088
<i>Now, I have no fortune,</i>

00:42.122 --> 00:44.290
but I'm spilling over with affections,

00:44.324 --> 00:47.126
which I am ready to pour over you

00:47.160 --> 00:49.328
like applesauce over roast pork.

00:49.362 --> 00:50.463
[laughter]

00:50.497 --> 00:52.298
I am aware, Mr. Trenchard,

00:52.332 --> 00:56.135
that you are not used to the
manners of good society,

00:56.169 --> 00:59.638
and that alone will
excuse the impertinence

00:59.673 --> 01:01.574
of which you are guilty.

01:01.608 --> 01:04.477
Don't know the
manners of good society, eh?

01:04.510 --> 01:05.644
[laughs]

01:05.679 --> 01:07.279
Well, I guess I know enough

01:07.314 --> 01:09.181
to turn you inside out, old gal,

01:09.216 --> 01:12.318
you sockdologizing old man-trap.

01:12.352 --> 01:13.986
[laughter]

01:14.020 --> 01:15.421
[gunshot]

01:15.455 --> 01:17.690
[women scream, crowd commotion]

01:17.724 --> 01:21.627
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

01:21.661 --> 01:23.629
[audience gasping]

01:23.663 --> 01:29.935
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:29.970 --> 01:33.172
Sic semper tyrannis!

01:33.206 --> 01:35.274
The South shall be free!

01:35.308 --> 01:42.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:49.356 --> 01:50.723
Who was that on the phone?

01:50.757 --> 01:52.224
I have to go.

01:52.259 --> 01:53.859
Now? Where?

01:53.894 --> 01:55.027
Something came up at work.

01:55.061 --> 01:56.462
No, no, you can't just...

01:56.496 --> 01:57.830
Lucy.

01:57.864 --> 01:59.965
What the hell's gotten into you?

02:00.000 --> 02:01.167
Who's Amy?

02:01.201 --> 02:02.401
I'm... I'm...

02:02.435 --> 02:04.236
I'm sorry.

02:04.271 --> 02:06.238
I'm sorry. Amy... Amy is a friend.

02:06.273 --> 02:09.842
And, uh, she's from
work, and she needs my help.

02:09.876 --> 02:11.177
Okay?

02:11.211 --> 02:12.745
Mm-hmm.

02:14.614 --> 02:16.081
Come here.

02:17.217 --> 02:19.218
I really am glad to see you.

02:21.621 --> 02:23.255
Okay.

02:23.290 --> 02:26.392
Don't... don't
forget about tomorrow night.

02:26.426 --> 02:28.194
Yeah.

02:32.899 --> 02:36.068
[background chatter]

02:37.704 --> 02:39.838
So Flynn took out the
Mothership again, huh?

02:39.873 --> 02:41.040
Where'd he go?

02:41.074 --> 02:42.251
I don't know. I just got here.

02:42.275 --> 02:43.676
Hey.

02:43.710 --> 02:45.277
- What's changed in your lives?
- Wh...

02:45.312 --> 02:48.547
Since we got back from
1937, what has changed for you?

02:48.582 --> 02:49.959
I just had an unsuccessful evening

02:49.983 --> 02:51.260
with a girl, so nothing, really.

02:51.284 --> 02:52.251
Why? What's wrong?

02:52.285 --> 02:53.252
My sister's gone.

02:53.286 --> 02:54.587
Gone? Gone where?

02:54.621 --> 02:57.256
Gone as in erased from history.

02:57.290 --> 03:00.062
Something that Flynn did or
we did to the "Hindenburg"

03:00.063 --> 03:01.193
has changed my family.

03:01.228 --> 03:03.539
My mother isn't sick anymore,
and my sister was never born.

03:03.563 --> 03:05.464
Lucy, we have a dossier on you,

03:05.498 --> 03:07.399
and it doesn't say
anything about a sister.

03:07.434 --> 03:09.735
Look, this is her right here.

03:09.769 --> 03:12.471
You wore this on the trip back to 1937?

03:12.505 --> 03:14.640
That is incredible.

03:14.674 --> 03:18.377
You took it from a timeline
where your sister existed,

03:18.411 --> 03:20.646
carried it here, to where she doesn't.

03:20.680 --> 03:23.415
I do not share your
excitement, Mr. Mason.

03:23.450 --> 03:25.451
Whatever changed, you
have to change back.

03:25.485 --> 03:26.952
- Change it back.
- I'm sorry, Lucy,

03:26.987 --> 03:28.554
but Flynn is hours ahead of us.

03:28.588 --> 03:29.668
- We don't have time for this.
- Why not?

03:29.669 --> 03:30.853
We have a time machine, don't we?

03:30.854 --> 03:32.737
Flynn could be
decimating history right now.

03:32.738 --> 03:34.893
Our reality could
change like that any second.

03:34.919 --> 03:36.439
- You need to go.
- Not until we figure this out.

03:36.463 --> 03:37.496
- Lucy...
- Hey.

03:37.530 --> 03:38.590
You dragged her into all this.

03:38.591 --> 03:41.600
She just lost her sister.
Give her a damn minute.

03:41.635 --> 03:45.271
Flynn went back to April 14, 1865.

03:45.305 --> 03:46.805
Now, you need to get moving,

03:46.840 --> 03:48.407
and you need to eliminate Garcia Flynn.

03:48.441 --> 03:49.441
Are we clear?

03:49.476 --> 03:52.244
<i>[tense music]</i>

03:52.279 --> 03:53.612
Yeah.

03:53.647 --> 03:55.180
Yeah, okay.

03:55.215 --> 03:57.816
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:57.851 --> 04:00.953
Wait, what's April 14, 1865?

04:00.987 --> 04:02.354
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:02.389 --> 04:04.957
The assassination of Abraham Lincoln.

04:04.991 --> 04:10.329
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:10.363 --> 04:12.798
Hey, uh, I can try to figure out

04:12.832 --> 04:15.434
what happened to your
sister, if you want.

04:15.468 --> 04:16.969
How?

04:17.003 --> 04:19.004
Something happened on the "Hindenburg"

04:19.039 --> 04:20.505
that affected your parents somehow.

04:20.540 --> 04:22.474
I can look for a connection, you know,

04:22.509 --> 04:24.977
try to see what changed.

04:25.011 --> 04:28.314
Tell me your parents' names, birthdays,

04:28.348 --> 04:29.915
anything that can help.

04:32.886 --> 04:34.720
You would do that for me?

04:36.423 --> 04:37.690
Come on.

04:37.724 --> 04:39.325
- Here.
- Yeah, okay.

04:41.161 --> 04:42.194
[sighs]

04:42.228 --> 04:46.065
<i>[somber music]</i>

04:46.099 --> 04:47.566
[sighs] This is crazy.

04:51.271 --> 04:52.705
Garcia Flynn.

04:52.739 --> 04:54.740
[sighs] He went straight for Anthony.

04:54.774 --> 04:56.975
He knew he was the project leader,

04:57.010 --> 04:59.345
the best of our only two pilots.

04:59.379 --> 05:01.880
So how did Flynn know so much about us,

05:01.915 --> 05:04.216
our vulnerabilities?

05:09.456 --> 05:10.889
Is there a problem?

05:10.924 --> 05:12.658
What do they do with these recordings?

05:12.692 --> 05:14.893
Why does Rittenhouse even need them?

05:14.928 --> 05:18.464
Don't speak that
name out loud ever again.

05:25.205 --> 05:28.607
<i>[PA announcement in background]</i>

05:28.641 --> 05:31.443
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

05:31.478 --> 05:34.713
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:34.748 --> 05:36.615
Trick-or-treat.

05:36.649 --> 05:39.451
Trust me, no one is
more worried than I am

05:39.486 --> 05:41.086
that I am not a real soldier.

05:41.121 --> 05:42.755
Where did these
getups even come from?

05:42.789 --> 05:44.356
Civil War re-enactors club.

05:44.391 --> 05:46.425
No wonder they smell like
sweat and loneliness.

05:46.459 --> 05:51.563
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:51.598 --> 05:53.132
- Okay, uh... whoa, whoa!
- Sorry.

05:53.166 --> 05:54.633
Just sit.

05:54.667 --> 05:55.934
[sighs]

05:55.969 --> 05:58.003
Here. Let me.

06:01.941 --> 06:02.912
I was really hoping

06:02.913 --> 06:05.450
I'd never have to get in
this damn thing again.

06:09.249 --> 06:11.083
Lucy, I'm sorry about your sister.

06:11.117 --> 06:13.328
Thank you...

06:14.487 --> 06:16.522
for backing me with Agent Christopher.

06:20.527 --> 06:24.062
Trust me. We're gonna fix it.

06:24.097 --> 06:26.231
We're gonna fix everything.

06:26.266 --> 06:27.599
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

06:27.634 --> 06:29.268
<i>Prepare for launch sequence.</i>

06:29.302 --> 06:31.904
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:31.938 --> 06:34.940
<i>Life support systems currently online.</i>

06:36.000 --> 06:42.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

06:47.787 --> 06:48.787
[mutters]

06:54.894 --> 06:59.198
<i>[dramatic musical build-up]</i>

07:05.505 --> 07:08.874
We really should get some paperweights.

07:10.643 --> 07:13.378
[insects chirping]

07:19.219 --> 07:22.488
<i>[mechanical power-down thrumming]</i>

07:22.522 --> 07:24.857
Tell me this gets easier.

07:24.891 --> 07:26.859
It doesn't.

07:35.902 --> 07:38.170
<i>[soft music]</i>

07:38.204 --> 07:42.140
[popping, whistling]

07:42.175 --> 07:43.775
What's all that?

07:45.845 --> 07:48.341
The Civil War just ended.

07:50.250 --> 07:52.751
They're celebrating.

07:54.354 --> 07:57.356
[people cheering]

08:04.864 --> 08:06.265
Praise to Lincoln!

08:06.299 --> 08:13.272
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:16.476 --> 08:18.110
Mr. Booth.

08:18.144 --> 08:20.078
I'm quite the admirer of yours.

08:20.113 --> 08:21.446
Oh?

08:21.481 --> 08:22.881
What production did you see me in?

08:22.916 --> 08:24.349
"Richard III"?

08:24.384 --> 08:25.918
Oh, I'm not talking about a play.

08:25.952 --> 08:28.420
I know what you're about to do.

08:28.454 --> 08:31.423
<i>[dramatic musical sting]</i>

08:32.659 --> 08:35.760
I think I can help.

08:36.600 --> 08:40.818
- <font color="#D81D1D">Synced and corrected by VitoSilans</font> -
-- <font color="#138CE9">www.Addic7ed.com</font> --

08:41.379 --> 08:43.500
Yah!

08:43.534 --> 08:46.803
<i>[soft music]</i>

08:46.838 --> 08:49.139
- [horse whinnies]
- [background chatter]

08:49.173 --> 08:56.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:56.881 --> 08:59.316
Check out that swagger.

08:59.350 --> 09:01.351
The Civil War just ended.

09:01.386 --> 09:02.690
Slavery's outlawed.

09:02.859 --> 09:05.822
African-Americans
thought their future was bright...

09:05.857 --> 09:08.725
which pretty much ends
tonight when Lincoln's shot.

09:10.437 --> 09:12.338
So what do you think Flynn is up to?

09:12.372 --> 09:14.283
He's got to be here to
change the assassination.

09:14.307 --> 09:15.559
- But how?
- I don't know.

09:15.678 --> 09:18.421
But I do know exactly where John
Wilkes Booth's going to be,

09:18.445 --> 09:19.778
so we start there.

09:19.813 --> 09:21.614
Best guess, he takes us to Flynn.

09:21.648 --> 09:24.617
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

09:24.651 --> 09:26.252
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:26.286 --> 09:28.454
So Booth walks into Ford's Theatre

09:28.488 --> 09:30.689
at exactly 10:00 a.m., huh?

09:30.724 --> 09:32.625
Not 9:56, 10:07?

09:32.659 --> 09:34.126
Hundreds of books have been written

09:34.160 --> 09:35.527
about Booth's movements today.

09:35.562 --> 09:37.529
Let me guess. You read them all.

09:37.564 --> 09:38.964
And wrote one of them.

09:38.999 --> 09:40.899
So why is Booth coming here now?

09:40.934 --> 09:42.605
What, is he scouting for tonight?

09:42.606 --> 09:43.936
No, he's an actor.

09:43.970 --> 09:46.038
He knew Ford's Theatre like
the back of his hand,

09:46.072 --> 09:47.539
used it as his mailing address,

09:47.574 --> 09:49.408
picks up his mail at exactly 10:00 a.m.

09:49.442 --> 09:51.053
- An actor.
- Pretty well known too.

09:51.054 --> 09:52.421
But his brother, Edwin, was literally

09:52.445 --> 09:54.713
the most famous actor in America.

09:54.748 --> 09:56.248
John never quite measured up.

09:56.283 --> 09:57.660
So this is like if Donnie Wahlberg

09:57.684 --> 09:59.718
assassinated the president?

09:59.753 --> 10:02.087
Pretty much, actually.

10:02.122 --> 10:03.122
Come on.

10:03.156 --> 10:04.556
Hey, keep an eye out, huh?

10:04.591 --> 10:06.592
If you find Booth or
Flynn, come get us fast.

10:06.626 --> 10:08.627
Let's go.

10:10.497 --> 10:13.766
<i>[dramatic instrumentals]</i>

10:13.800 --> 10:15.467
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:15.502 --> 10:17.636
Right this way.

10:17.671 --> 10:19.438
Hello.

10:21.474 --> 10:23.909
Any of your books tell
you where the mailboxes were?

10:23.943 --> 10:25.611
No. Let's split up.

10:25.645 --> 10:27.313
- Okay.
- Okay.

10:28.682 --> 10:29.982
- You want...
- No, I got it.

10:30.016 --> 10:31.016
Okay.

10:39.626 --> 10:41.293
You all right there, Sergeant?

10:41.328 --> 10:42.594
Yes, I am. [clears throat]

10:42.629 --> 10:45.464
A sergeant. And just fine.

10:45.498 --> 10:46.799
What's your name?

10:46.833 --> 10:48.967
Um, Denzel... Washington.

10:49.002 --> 10:50.769
I'm Nicholas. Whereabouts you from?

10:50.804 --> 10:51.937
- Chicago.
- Oh.

10:51.971 --> 10:53.472
You was free when you signed up.

10:53.506 --> 10:55.841
You got kin or young
folk still in bondage?

10:55.875 --> 10:59.778
No, my... my family was all born free.

10:59.813 --> 11:02.481
So y... you read and write good, huh?

11:02.515 --> 11:04.616
Pretty good, yeah.

11:04.651 --> 11:06.652
[laughs] That's
how you got them stripes.

11:06.686 --> 11:08.354
Hey, boys, get on over here.

11:08.388 --> 11:10.189
Old Denzel's gonna
write our notices for us.

11:10.223 --> 11:12.157
We need you to write something
for the newspaper.

11:12.192 --> 11:13.369
You go ahead and start with mine.

11:13.393 --> 11:14.516
I... I can't write that.

11:14.517 --> 11:16.662
"The Colored Tennessean"
prints them free.

11:16.696 --> 11:20.165
Uh, Nicholas Biddle, 2nd Regiment,

11:20.200 --> 11:21.467
Colored Infantry.

11:21.501 --> 11:23.268
[chuckles] That's me.

11:26.773 --> 11:29.308
Nicholas Biddle of the 2nd Regiment,

11:29.342 --> 11:30.876
Colored Infantry,

11:30.910 --> 11:32.411
wishes to learn the whereabouts

11:32.445 --> 11:34.346
of his wife and four children.

11:34.381 --> 11:37.750
The children are
Selia, Sarah, Elizabeth,

11:37.784 --> 11:38.884
and Adam Lee.

11:38.918 --> 11:41.587
My wife's Anne,

11:41.621 --> 11:43.322
and the last I seen
her was in a sale pen

11:43.356 --> 11:46.859
of a human trader named
Robert Clark, Atlanta.

11:46.893 --> 11:49.728
<i>[somber music]</i>

11:49.763 --> 11:53.198
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:53.233 --> 11:56.201
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

11:56.236 --> 12:03.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:07.480 --> 12:10.015
Oh, pardon me, miss.

12:10.049 --> 12:12.451
I'm General Grant's aide.

12:12.485 --> 12:13.952
You're Robert Todd Lincoln.

12:13.987 --> 12:14.953
Have we met?

12:14.988 --> 12:16.855
No. [laughs]

12:16.890 --> 12:19.258
I... I admire your father.

12:19.292 --> 12:22.327
Pleased to meet you, Miss...

12:24.230 --> 12:27.332
Juliet Shakes... man.

12:29.335 --> 12:30.369
Are you an actress?

12:30.403 --> 12:31.737
No. Yes.

12:31.771 --> 12:33.372
Not a very good one.

12:33.406 --> 12:34.473
Just starting out.

12:34.507 --> 12:35.874
Something rarer than an actress:

12:35.909 --> 12:36.909
a modest one.

12:36.943 --> 12:38.544
[laughs]

12:38.578 --> 12:40.347
General Grant was supposed
to attend tonight's play,

12:40.348 --> 12:42.825
but he can't make it and I
have to return his tickets.

12:42.849 --> 12:44.994
Well, I'll take the tickets
to the box office for you.

12:45.018 --> 12:46.962
I'd like to leave a note
too with the general's apologies.

12:46.986 --> 12:48.987
Of course.

12:49.022 --> 12:50.122
Take your time.

12:55.261 --> 12:57.429
You know, my father's coming
to the play tonight.

12:57.464 --> 12:58.497
Have you seen it?

12:58.531 --> 13:00.599
It's... not very good.

13:00.633 --> 13:02.468
No?

13:02.502 --> 13:04.136
Should I tell him not to come?

13:09.209 --> 13:12.945
Having President Lincoln for a father,

13:12.979 --> 13:15.314
what is that like for you?

13:17.350 --> 13:21.253
He casts a long shadow, but it's...

13:21.287 --> 13:23.922
not one I mind living in.

13:23.957 --> 13:26.124
I'm proud of him, he's
done some great things.

13:26.159 --> 13:27.459
I agree.

13:27.494 --> 13:29.728
And he's just getting started.

13:36.569 --> 13:38.770
So what are you gonna
do once you find your family?

13:38.805 --> 13:40.816
I'm gonna work me a
piece of my old master's land.

13:40.840 --> 13:42.307
You think the man who owned you

13:42.342 --> 13:43.809
is just gonna give you his land?

13:43.843 --> 13:45.177
No, I think President Lincoln's

13:45.211 --> 13:46.845
gonna make him.

13:46.880 --> 13:49.348
It's all smooth
sailing from here on out.

13:49.382 --> 13:51.316
What's that supposed to mean?

13:51.351 --> 13:52.985
Uh, I'm sorry. Nothing.

13:53.019 --> 13:55.621
I didn't... [ahem]...
I didn't mean anything.

13:55.655 --> 13:58.190
What regiment you in?

13:58.224 --> 14:00.726
Uh, the 4th. Colored.

14:00.760 --> 14:01.827
- Hmm.
- Infantry.

14:01.861 --> 14:02.695
4th Colored.

14:02.696 --> 14:05.631
Yeah, I never, uh, never heard of it.

14:05.665 --> 14:07.332
Whereabouts y'all fight?

14:07.367 --> 14:08.700
We fought all over.

14:08.735 --> 14:10.669
See, this ain't no real uniform.

14:10.703 --> 14:12.971
You pretending to be a solider, huh?

14:13.006 --> 14:14.039
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

14:14.073 --> 14:15.173
After what we went through?

14:15.208 --> 14:17.009
Why, so you can get you a girl?

14:17.043 --> 14:18.377
Look like some big hero?

14:18.411 --> 14:20.245
Yeah, go on, you lying rat!

14:23.683 --> 14:24.750
Miss Shakesman?

14:24.784 --> 14:26.184
It has been a pleasure.

14:26.219 --> 14:27.920
I'll see they get it right away.

14:27.954 --> 14:29.354
Please do, yes.

14:29.389 --> 14:31.557
<i>[ominous music]</i>

14:31.591 --> 14:33.659
John Wilkes Booth.

14:33.693 --> 14:35.060
Robert Lincoln.

14:35.094 --> 14:37.829
I... I saw you on stage here last month.

14:37.864 --> 14:40.332
Of course. Why are you here?

14:40.366 --> 14:41.733
My father invited General Grant

14:41.768 --> 14:43.035
to see tonight's play,

14:43.069 --> 14:45.103
and I'm helping him escape it.

14:45.138 --> 14:47.573
I assume you know Miss Shakesman.

14:47.607 --> 14:49.575
- John Booth.
- She's an actress.

14:49.609 --> 14:52.844
Really? Where do you perform?

14:52.879 --> 14:54.413
I'm new to the profession.

14:54.447 --> 14:56.081
And very humble.

14:56.115 --> 14:58.617
Miss Shakesman, do you
know that Mr. Booth's brother

14:58.651 --> 15:00.018
saved my life on a train platform

15:00.053 --> 15:01.453
just last year?

15:01.487 --> 15:04.456
Pulled me out of the
path of an oncoming train.

15:04.490 --> 15:05.724
It's a true story.

15:05.758 --> 15:08.093
- Amazing.
- That's Edwin.

15:08.127 --> 15:10.195
- Always the hero.
- Yes, sir.

15:10.229 --> 15:12.798
The Lincolns owe the
Booths a great debt.

15:12.832 --> 15:16.768
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:16.803 --> 15:19.771
<i>[ominous music]</i>

15:19.806 --> 15:25.444
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:29.015 --> 15:30.382
So we're 1,000% sure

15:30.416 --> 15:32.217
we can't just shoot this asshat,

15:32.251 --> 15:33.785
save Lincoln here and now?

15:33.820 --> 15:35.287
Believe me, I want to.

15:35.321 --> 15:36.888
It might change things too much.

15:36.923 --> 15:38.667
Like maybe there'll
be a lot less lynchings.

15:38.691 --> 15:40.158
- [sighs]
- I'm serious.

15:40.193 --> 15:42.427
I'm serious. I just
met some black soldiers.

15:42.462 --> 15:44.096
We know Lincoln's death...

15:44.130 --> 15:45.564
It's gonna be a disaster for them,

15:45.598 --> 15:47.899
not to mention my
great-great-grandparents.

15:47.934 --> 15:50.469
Don't look at me. I'm with him.

15:50.503 --> 15:51.837
[sighs]

15:54.173 --> 15:55.607
Look, I understand,

15:55.642 --> 15:58.310
but we don't know the
consequences. It's too risky.

15:58.344 --> 15:59.811
It's our job to protect history.

15:59.846 --> 16:01.146
Yeah, rich white guys' history.

16:01.180 --> 16:02.814
A lot of my history sucks.

16:02.849 --> 16:04.449
Look, I know it seems crazy,

16:04.484 --> 16:07.953
but maybe we can change
things for the better.

16:07.987 --> 16:09.821
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:09.856 --> 16:10.956
Psst!

16:10.990 --> 16:17.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:22.235 --> 16:24.336
This is the Herndon House,

16:24.370 --> 16:27.139
where Booth meets with his conspirators.

16:27.173 --> 16:28.473
What conspirators?

16:28.508 --> 16:30.475
- [gasps]
- Get back, get back!

16:31.711 --> 16:34.146
When I shoot, you run. Stay low.

16:34.180 --> 16:36.314
- Don't stop for anything!
- But what about you?

16:36.349 --> 16:38.517
- [bullets ricocheting]
- I'm right behind you.

16:38.551 --> 16:39.618
Go! Go!

16:39.652 --> 16:46.658
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:48.695 --> 16:49.695
Ah!

16:52.065 --> 16:54.466
Ah!

16:54.500 --> 16:57.035
- What happened?
- Nothing. Come on! Go!

16:57.070 --> 17:00.772
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:05.012 --> 17:07.646
Your brother looks to
be at the fag end of things.

17:07.680 --> 17:09.181
Poor digestion's all.

17:09.214 --> 17:10.983
I thank you very much, ma'am.

17:11.017 --> 17:13.551
Thank you.

17:15.588 --> 17:18.557
Oh! Where the hell is
Rufus with the supplies?

17:18.590 --> 17:19.590
You need a real doctor.

17:19.626 --> 17:21.727
To do what? Leech me?

17:21.761 --> 17:24.363
Oh! Ah...

17:24.396 --> 17:26.098
Get this off me.

17:26.132 --> 17:27.432
Okay.

17:27.467 --> 17:28.867
Ah, ah.

17:28.902 --> 17:30.936
This would take 15
minutes to patch back home.

17:30.937 --> 17:32.114
Here, I'm gonna die of sepsis.

17:32.138 --> 17:33.138
[door opens]

17:34.440 --> 17:36.441
- You get it? Okay.
- Yeah.

17:36.476 --> 17:37.843
Oh!

17:37.877 --> 17:40.212
Rufus, you're up.

17:40.246 --> 17:41.580
My knife's in the pocket.

17:41.614 --> 17:43.382
You gotta sterilize it over the lamp.

17:43.416 --> 17:45.684
Um... what?

17:45.718 --> 17:47.236
The bullet's still in there.

17:47.237 --> 17:49.231
It's just under the skin,
but you gotta take it out.

17:49.255 --> 17:50.455
Why me?

17:50.490 --> 17:51.957
Because you work with your hands.

17:51.991 --> 17:53.358
Yeah, on circuit boards.

17:53.393 --> 17:54.927
Think of me as a circuit board...

17:54.961 --> 17:57.563
that's gonna die if you don't help.

17:57.597 --> 17:59.598
Don't look at me. I faint.

17:59.632 --> 18:01.133
[groans]

18:02.168 --> 18:04.102
So those weapons Flynn has.

18:04.137 --> 18:05.881
Why does he need that
kind of firepower, huh?

18:05.905 --> 18:07.406
Lincoln gets killed anyway.

18:07.440 --> 18:09.074
I don't think it's just about Lincoln.

18:09.108 --> 18:11.977
Lincoln's death was part
of a much larger conspiracy

18:12.011 --> 18:13.889
to kill the four most powerful
men in government

18:13.913 --> 18:15.247
in one fell swoop:

18:15.281 --> 18:16.815
Lincoln, Vice President Johnson,

18:16.849 --> 18:18.650
Secretary of State
Seward, and General Grant.

18:18.685 --> 18:20.319
It would have been devastating,

18:20.353 --> 18:21.985
but the other shooters
never followed through

18:21.986 --> 18:24.156
or just failed outright.

18:24.190 --> 18:26.068
Well, that's before they
had semiautomatic weapons.

18:26.092 --> 18:27.292
<i>[tense music]</i>

18:27.327 --> 18:29.795
Exactly.

18:29.829 --> 18:32.898
What if Flynn is trying
to help them succeed?

18:32.932 --> 18:35.634
They would cripple the Union,
maybe revive the Confederacy.

18:35.668 --> 18:38.136
Hell, Johnson and Grant are supposed
to become presidents.

18:38.171 --> 18:40.072
America as we know it would
be unrecognizable.

18:40.106 --> 18:41.506
Okay, so how do we stop all that?

18:41.541 --> 18:43.075
One problem at a time.

18:43.109 --> 18:44.620
Grant takes a train out of town at 6:00.

18:44.644 --> 18:45.854
I need to make sure he's on it.

18:45.878 --> 18:47.646
You take care of Wyatt.

18:47.680 --> 18:49.314
We're gonna need you tonight.

18:53.353 --> 18:55.787
This is gonna be the
worst game of Operation ever.

18:58.558 --> 18:59.591
Zzzzz!

18:59.626 --> 19:00.592
[laughs]

19:00.627 --> 19:01.827
Go on.

19:04.130 --> 19:07.966
[metallic clanging]

19:20.079 --> 19:21.780
[clanging]

19:21.814 --> 19:23.649
Thank you, sir.

19:23.683 --> 19:25.384
Miss Shakesman?

19:27.220 --> 19:28.083
Mr. Lincoln.

19:28.241 --> 19:29.531
What are you doing here?

19:29.555 --> 19:32.190
Following you, it seems.

19:32.225 --> 19:34.459
I'm a lucky man, then.

19:34.494 --> 19:36.161
What happened to the train?

19:36.195 --> 19:38.330
Technically speaking, it broke.

19:38.364 --> 19:39.698
Oh.

19:39.732 --> 19:41.233
Much to General Grant's dismay,

19:41.267 --> 19:43.468
he and I will be seeing a play tonight.

19:43.503 --> 19:44.836
No!

19:44.871 --> 19:47.339
Like I said before, it's a terrible play.

19:47.373 --> 19:48.507
The general will hate it.

19:48.541 --> 19:50.142
[laughs] Maybe.

19:50.176 --> 19:53.011
But the general and I
are already committed.

19:53.046 --> 19:54.413
But is there any chance

19:54.447 --> 19:56.148
that you'd like to see a terrible play?

19:56.182 --> 19:57.382
What?

19:57.417 --> 19:58.650
Excuse me for being forward,

19:58.685 --> 20:00.152
but would you come as my guest?

20:00.186 --> 20:02.087
You'd improve the evening a great deal.

20:02.121 --> 20:03.922
We've met twice in one day.

20:03.956 --> 20:06.091
That can't just be a coincidence.

20:07.193 --> 20:10.195
Do you believe in fate?

20:10.229 --> 20:14.199
<i>[light music]</i>

20:14.233 --> 20:15.600
I'm at the National.

20:15.635 --> 20:16.702
The National.

20:16.736 --> 20:18.203
At 7:00, then.

20:19.739 --> 20:22.240
[both laugh]

20:22.275 --> 20:29.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:29.248 --> 20:33.552
We really have to
stop meeting like this, Lucy.

20:36.255 --> 20:38.590
You son of a bitch.

20:38.624 --> 20:40.292
My sister is gone, disappeared

20:40.326 --> 20:42.318
because of something you
did to the "Hindenburg."

20:42.319 --> 20:44.340
It's war. I lost my whole family.

20:44.356 --> 20:45.556
Because you murdered them.

20:45.590 --> 20:46.824
Rittenhouse murdered them.

20:46.858 --> 20:48.025
I asked about Rittenhouse,

20:48.059 --> 20:49.560
and no one's never heard of him.

20:49.594 --> 20:51.261
Rittenhouse isn't a him. It's a they.

20:51.296 --> 20:54.198
And that's why I'm here:
to right some wrongs.

20:54.232 --> 20:55.666
By shooting up half of Washington?

20:55.700 --> 20:57.167
Trying to destroy America outright?

20:57.202 --> 20:58.736
I'm not trying to destroy America.

20:58.770 --> 21:00.604
I'm trying to save it!

21:00.638 --> 21:03.340
Lucy, one day

21:03.375 --> 21:05.042
you are going to help me.

21:05.076 --> 21:07.177
Or what? You'll kill me?

21:07.212 --> 21:09.213
That's not a threat.

21:09.247 --> 21:10.848
It's your future.

21:10.882 --> 21:13.851
So accept it, and stop
trying to interfere.

21:13.885 --> 21:15.619
What are you trying to do?

21:15.653 --> 21:17.354
What does this have
to do with Rittenhouse?

21:17.389 --> 21:18.422
Tell me!

21:18.456 --> 21:21.725
Don't get in my way again.

21:21.760 --> 21:24.728
<i>[tense music]</i>

21:24.763 --> 21:27.598
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:31.231 --> 21:33.098
Is it unsanitary if
I throw up on you now?

21:39.857 --> 21:42.726
Um... you went shopping?

21:42.838 --> 21:45.273
Robert Lincoln invited me to a play.

21:45.307 --> 21:47.609
A play? You mean the play?

21:47.643 --> 21:48.987
General Grant's gonna be there tonight.

21:49.011 --> 21:50.078
Flynn sabotaged his train.

21:50.112 --> 21:52.247
You saw Flynn.

21:52.281 --> 21:54.382
I saw him leaving the train station.

21:56.118 --> 21:58.453
The point is, Grant's
gonna be there tonight,

21:58.487 --> 21:59.821
and I've gotta save him.

21:59.855 --> 22:01.056
How, exactly?

22:01.090 --> 22:02.323
I don't know.

22:02.358 --> 22:04.259
I'll, uh, get Grant out of the balcony

22:04.303 --> 22:06.432
before Booth shows up... somehow.

22:06.494 --> 22:08.740
I'm pretty sure we can come
up with a better plan than that.

22:08.764 --> 22:10.398
Will these help?

22:10.433 --> 22:11.733
[breathing heavily]

22:11.767 --> 22:13.435
And I assume with all that,

22:13.469 --> 22:15.470
we're gonna save everybody but Lincoln?

22:15.504 --> 22:17.105
Rufus...

22:17.139 --> 22:19.574
All you have to do is open
your mouth to save him.

22:19.608 --> 22:21.943
And you're just gonna let
Booth shoot him in the head?

22:21.977 --> 22:24.179
Do you think any of this is easy for me?

22:24.213 --> 22:26.414
My whole life, I've idolized Lincoln.

22:26.449 --> 22:29.284
When I was a little girl, I
would memorize his speeches.

22:29.318 --> 22:30.852
Well, then do something.

22:30.886 --> 22:32.926
We would come back to an
entirely different world.

22:32.955 --> 22:34.689
Who knows if it would be better

22:34.723 --> 22:37.492
or if there would be
anything left to come back to at all?

22:37.526 --> 22:40.028
The present isn't perfect, but it's ours.

22:40.062 --> 22:41.429
Awful as it is,

22:41.464 --> 22:43.631
what happens to Lincoln is meant to be.

22:45.835 --> 22:47.969
What about my wife?

22:48.003 --> 22:49.504
'Cause by your logic, you're saying

22:49.538 --> 22:52.540
that bad things like my wife's death

22:52.575 --> 22:55.977
are meant to be.

22:56.011 --> 22:57.479
You wouldn't use the time machine

22:57.513 --> 22:59.114
to save her either?

22:59.148 --> 23:02.117
<i>[solemn music]</i>

23:02.151 --> 23:05.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:06.021 --> 23:08.223
Wow.

23:08.257 --> 23:11.626
You are saying that.

23:11.660 --> 23:16.192
So... your sister is supposed to live,

23:16.255 --> 23:17.866
and my wife is supposed to die.

23:17.900 --> 23:19.334
- Is that it?
- That's not fair.

23:19.368 --> 23:21.536
You just lost your sister,

23:21.570 --> 23:23.371
and you're gonna sit
next to Robert Lincoln

23:23.405 --> 23:25.039
and let him lose his father?

23:25.074 --> 23:32.080
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:35.751 --> 23:37.218
Never seen nothing like it.

23:37.253 --> 23:38.853
Where'd you get these?

23:38.888 --> 23:41.823
We're Prussian. We make good guns.

23:41.857 --> 23:44.359
Sic semper tyrannis.

23:44.393 --> 23:45.960
The South shall be free.

23:47.429 --> 23:49.531
Use this instead.

23:49.565 --> 23:51.266
It's ugly.

23:51.300 --> 23:52.700
It fires 17 bullets.

23:52.735 --> 23:53.712
You won't need the knife.

23:53.736 --> 23:56.838
I like the knife.

23:56.872 --> 23:58.173
Just take it.

23:58.207 --> 24:01.109
The Derringer is more dramatic.

24:01.143 --> 24:04.779
Now, I appreciate the
weaponry you provided us, sir,

24:04.813 --> 24:07.916
but I have staked my fortune and fame

24:07.950 --> 24:10.084
on this spectacle,

24:10.119 --> 24:13.288
and I will see it
through as I imagined it.

24:13.322 --> 24:17.258
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

24:17.293 --> 24:18.860
<i>[knocking at door]</i>

24:18.894 --> 24:21.029
<i>Mr. Robert Todd Lincoln downstairs</i>

24:21.063 --> 24:22.764
<i>for Miss Shakesman.</i>

24:22.798 --> 24:23.878
I'll be down in a minute.

24:25.267 --> 24:26.801
Um...

24:37.446 --> 24:38.913
Now, please.

24:38.948 --> 24:41.449
You'll save Secretary of State Seward?

24:41.483 --> 24:43.551
And you'll save Vice President Johnson?

24:43.586 --> 24:44.619
Yeah, we got it.

24:45.654 --> 24:48.423
Lucy, just...

24:48.457 --> 24:50.491
think about who you save.

24:50.526 --> 24:53.494
<i>[gentle music]</i>

24:53.529 --> 24:59.067
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:59.101 --> 25:01.803
<i>You wouldn't treat him
as some other people would</i>

25:01.837 --> 25:04.572
when you found out that he was not

25:04.607 --> 25:07.342
the inheritor of that fortune.

25:07.376 --> 25:09.811
Not the heir of the fortune?

25:09.845 --> 25:12.614
No. [laughter]

25:12.648 --> 25:15.083
You people bark up the wrong tree

25:15.117 --> 25:17.118
about the old man's property.

25:17.152 --> 25:18.820
Which he left to you.

25:18.854 --> 25:20.355
Well... no.

25:20.389 --> 25:22.857
[laughter]

25:22.891 --> 25:25.360
He's always late.

25:25.394 --> 25:27.495
Oh?

25:27.529 --> 25:30.531
I wish I could be sure of that,

25:30.566 --> 25:33.501
for I have been cruelly disappointed

25:33.535 --> 25:35.003
in that particular.

25:35.037 --> 25:37.038
Yes, but we are old friends...

25:37.072 --> 25:40.041
["Hail to the Chief" playing]

25:40.075 --> 25:44.178
♪ ♪

25:44.213 --> 25:45.546
Miss Shakesman.

25:45.581 --> 25:47.782
Allow me to introduce my mother, Mary,

25:47.816 --> 25:49.384
and my father, the president.

25:49.418 --> 25:52.387
Father, please meet Juliet Shakesman.

25:52.421 --> 25:54.522
Miss Shakesman, how do you do?

25:54.556 --> 25:56.991
It's a great pleasure to meet you.

25:57.026 --> 26:04.032
♪ ♪

26:05.768 --> 26:07.035
[applause]

26:07.069 --> 26:10.538
[indistinct friendly shouting]

26:10.572 --> 26:17.178
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:17.212 --> 26:20.181
<i>[ominous music]</i>

26:20.223 --> 26:22.262
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:22.582 --> 26:24.988
So all I got to do

26:25.013 --> 26:27.243
is save the vice
president of the United States.

26:27.267 --> 26:28.601
Sure, no probs.

26:28.635 --> 26:30.436
[chuckles] Relax.

26:30.471 --> 26:32.238
This Atzerodt guy shows his face,

26:32.537 --> 26:35.172
just point him out to the vice
president's bodyguards.

26:35.207 --> 26:37.007
They'll do the rest. The
gun's just in case.

26:37.042 --> 26:38.542
What if I freeze?

26:38.577 --> 26:40.811
You won't.

26:44.282 --> 26:47.184
I, um... [clears throat]

26:47.219 --> 26:49.954
I grew up on the west side of Chicago,

26:49.988 --> 26:53.057
and there was a... there
was this kid, Rich Tannen,

26:53.091 --> 26:55.226
who used to come after me.

26:55.260 --> 26:56.927
But I wouldn't fight.

26:56.962 --> 26:58.129
There was no flight either.

26:58.163 --> 27:01.365
I just stood there. It was biological.

27:01.400 --> 27:03.667
Then he just beat the crap out of me.

27:05.670 --> 27:07.304
Rufus...

27:07.339 --> 27:08.572
I don't know you that well.

27:08.607 --> 27:09.807
But in the last two days,

27:09.841 --> 27:11.475
you helped us break out of jail.

27:11.510 --> 27:13.878
You held a knife to a Nazi's throat.

27:13.912 --> 27:17.548
And you pulled a bullet out
of my gut without puking.

27:17.582 --> 27:19.483
You won't freeze.

27:19.518 --> 27:21.285
I'm scared.

27:21.319 --> 27:23.421
I wouldn't go into battle
with you if you weren't.

27:27.092 --> 27:30.060
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

27:30.095 --> 27:31.729
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:31.763 --> 27:33.497
A woman of my age...

27:33.532 --> 27:35.900
Be you a woman of your age?

27:35.934 --> 27:38.335
[laughter]

27:38.370 --> 27:39.670
[coughing]

27:39.704 --> 27:41.472
- Are you all right?
- Oh, I'm just...

27:41.506 --> 27:45.276
- I'm just a little nervous.
- Would you like some water?

27:45.310 --> 27:48.412
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

27:48.447 --> 27:50.114
[laughter]

27:50.148 --> 27:51.248
Here, allow me.

27:51.283 --> 27:53.017
Oh, no, no. I'll get it.

27:53.051 --> 27:55.953
[laughter]

27:58.490 --> 28:01.559
- [dialogue continues]
- [laughter]

28:03.361 --> 28:07.097
- [dialogue continues]
- [laughter]

28:07.132 --> 28:08.532
[laughs]

28:08.567 --> 28:09.867
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:09.901 --> 28:11.268
- Good God!
- General...

28:11.303 --> 28:12.670
General Grant, please forgive me.

28:12.704 --> 28:13.704
Are you all right?

28:13.738 --> 28:16.140
I'm quite all right, yes.

28:16.174 --> 28:17.541
[ahem] Excuse me.

28:17.576 --> 28:18.976
- I'm so sorry.

28:19.010 --> 28:22.213
- You seem tickled to death.
- [laughter]

28:34.092 --> 28:35.826
The tall guy who gave you the gun.

28:35.861 --> 28:37.328
Where is he?

28:37.362 --> 28:41.232
<i>[tense music]</i>

28:41.266 --> 28:43.501
Why do I always get the big guys?

28:44.870 --> 28:47.204
[both grunting]

28:47.239 --> 28:54.245
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:03.121 --> 29:04.855
Father!

29:04.890 --> 29:06.690
Father, hurry.

29:06.725 --> 29:08.425
Oh, my goodness!

29:08.460 --> 29:11.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:11.363 --> 29:13.297
- [gunshots]
- [woman screams]

29:16.701 --> 29:18.602
What's going on?

29:18.637 --> 29:20.938
Mr. Secretary.

29:20.972 --> 29:23.941
<i>[tense music]</i>

29:23.975 --> 29:25.776
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:25.810 --> 29:27.077
Hey, Mr. Booth.

29:27.112 --> 29:28.612
Wife's been asking

29:28.647 --> 29:30.681
when we're gonna be seeing
you on stage again.

29:30.715 --> 29:33.250
<i>[intense suspenseful music]</i>

29:33.285 --> 29:34.585
Soon.

29:34.619 --> 29:41.625
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:46.798 --> 29:49.133
My friend's drunk. [chuckles]

29:49.167 --> 29:51.101
Unhand me!

29:51.136 --> 29:53.904
Grant's gonna be in there too.

29:53.939 --> 29:56.206
You're gonna need more than
one bullet. Take it!

29:56.241 --> 29:59.443
I set this course nigh
on four years ago

29:59.477 --> 30:02.446
and do not now submit my
destiny for your approval,

30:02.480 --> 30:04.114
nor...

30:08.486 --> 30:10.621
[sighs] Actors.

30:10.655 --> 30:13.324
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

30:13.358 --> 30:16.327
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:16.361 --> 30:18.429
Now, some other
gals and their mothers

30:18.463 --> 30:20.998
would go away when they found that out,

30:21.032 --> 30:23.334
but you value fortune, Ms. Gusty.

30:23.368 --> 30:24.969
[whispers] Robert.

30:25.003 --> 30:26.503
Yes.

30:27.973 --> 30:29.139
[door opens]

30:32.043 --> 30:35.279
- [sighs]
- [play dialogue continues]

30:35.313 --> 30:36.981
Miss Shakesman.

30:37.015 --> 30:38.582
[laughter]

30:38.617 --> 30:40.484
Mr. Trenchard...

30:40.518 --> 30:43.988
[dialogue continues indistinctly]

30:45.624 --> 30:47.458
It's not such a bad play.

30:47.492 --> 30:49.460
I'm offering her my heart and my hand.

30:49.494 --> 30:52.363
It's certainly not what I remembered.

30:52.397 --> 30:53.631
[laughs]

30:53.665 --> 30:55.265
[laughter]

30:55.300 --> 30:58.202
<i>[tense music]</i>

30:58.236 --> 31:05.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:32.437 --> 31:35.906
Well, if it ain't Sergeant
Denzel Washington.

31:35.940 --> 31:37.274
Excuse me.

31:39.878 --> 31:41.745
Why would you be sneaking around

31:41.780 --> 31:44.081
the vice president's hotel with this?

31:44.115 --> 31:45.192
Hey, boys, look who I found.

31:45.216 --> 31:46.650
Listen to me, Nicholas.

31:46.685 --> 31:48.218
I just need to talk to his bodyguards.

31:48.253 --> 31:49.893
I'm not trying to
hurt the vice president.

31:49.921 --> 31:51.088
I'm trying to save him.

31:51.122 --> 31:52.266
Oh, you are, huh? From what?

31:52.290 --> 31:53.390
There is a man in here

31:53.425 --> 31:55.059
who is going to kill him.

31:55.093 --> 31:56.493
Now, boys, hear that?

31:56.528 --> 31:58.228
The fake sergeant say

31:58.263 --> 32:00.831
he fixing to stop a man
from killing the vice president.

32:00.865 --> 32:01.932
Excuse me.

32:01.966 --> 32:04.935
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

32:04.969 --> 32:08.839
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:08.873 --> 32:10.340
He's gonna shoot him!

32:10.375 --> 32:12.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:12.644 --> 32:14.945
[gasps, screams]

32:17.615 --> 32:19.116
I wouldn't do that!

32:19.150 --> 32:21.285
[crowd commotion]

32:24.956 --> 32:27.257
- Move!
- Somebody call a doctor!

32:27.292 --> 32:28.859
Buy you a drink, Sergeant?

32:28.893 --> 32:30.527
I'm not a soldier.

32:30.562 --> 32:33.030
You are in my book.

32:33.064 --> 32:37.034
Don't know the
manners of good society, eh?

32:37.068 --> 32:40.738
Well, I guess I know enough to
turn you inside out, old gal,

32:40.772 --> 32:44.074
you sockdologizing old man-trap.

32:44.109 --> 32:47.311
[laughter]

32:47.345 --> 32:51.915
When I think of all I've thrown
away today in hard cash,

32:51.950 --> 32:57.654
I am apt to call
myself some awful hard names.

32:57.689 --> 33:00.124
$400,000...

33:00.158 --> 33:03.494
<i>[dramatic musical sting]</i>

33:03.528 --> 33:04.962
No! Mr. President!

33:04.996 --> 33:06.296
No!

33:06.331 --> 33:09.333
[screaming]

33:11.669 --> 33:14.638
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

33:14.672 --> 33:21.678
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:29.387 --> 33:31.021
[people scream]

33:31.055 --> 33:37.027
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:37.061 --> 33:40.464
[crowd gasping, yelling]

33:45.919 --> 33:48.519
The tall man who shot Lincoln,

33:48.554 --> 33:50.455
I saw him earlier with
John Wilkes Booth,

33:50.489 --> 33:51.756
whispering about something.

33:51.790 --> 33:54.325
I'd look for Booth.

33:56.061 --> 33:57.261
Excuse me, Officer.

33:57.296 --> 34:00.932
Yes, ma'am. Thank you.

34:00.966 --> 34:02.900
- Johnson?
- Alive.

34:02.935 --> 34:05.703
Hey.

34:05.738 --> 34:07.105
Seward's okay.

34:07.139 --> 34:09.907
- What about...
- Grant's safe.

34:09.942 --> 34:12.210
But Lincoln...

34:12.244 --> 34:14.212
Is the President safe?

34:14.246 --> 34:15.813
Where is the President now?

34:17.349 --> 34:18.750
What happens now?

34:18.784 --> 34:20.952
Please tell us something!

34:20.985 --> 34:23.054
<i>[solemn music]</i>

34:23.088 --> 34:25.656
Is the President well?

34:25.690 --> 34:29.360
[shouting indistinct questions]

34:34.699 --> 34:36.833
He's gone.

34:36.869 --> 34:38.569
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:38.603 --> 34:40.338
I am so sorry.

34:40.371 --> 34:43.241
Thank you for saving General Grant.

34:43.275 --> 34:45.409
The whole country thanks you.

34:45.444 --> 34:48.246
I wish I could have saved your father.

34:48.280 --> 34:50.281
There was nothing you could have done.

34:50.315 --> 34:52.850
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:52.885 --> 34:54.418
I have to go.

34:54.453 --> 34:56.254
Robert.

34:56.288 --> 35:03.294
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:11.203 --> 35:12.537
Listen.

35:12.571 --> 35:14.639
Don't go south.

35:14.673 --> 35:18.342
You find your family,
and you head up north.

35:18.377 --> 35:19.944
It's gonna be all right.

35:19.978 --> 35:21.045
All right?

35:21.080 --> 35:23.648
The man helped us, freed us,

35:23.682 --> 35:26.050
and they killed him for it.

35:28.387 --> 35:30.021
It'll never get better.

35:30.055 --> 35:31.722
It does.

35:31.757 --> 35:33.958
I promise you.

35:33.992 --> 35:37.528
It's not gonna be easy, but...

35:37.563 --> 35:40.131
it does get better.

35:40.165 --> 35:47.171
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:56.415 --> 35:58.816
Flynn's back in the present.

35:58.851 --> 36:00.785
Let's go home.

36:03.722 --> 36:07.091
I decided I was gonna let it happen.

36:07.126 --> 36:09.293
But then I called out to warn him.

36:11.530 --> 36:13.664
It was too late.

36:13.699 --> 36:15.733
It's one thing to talk about history

36:15.767 --> 36:19.904
like this abstract thing.

36:19.938 --> 36:25.276
But when the man gets
shot right in front of you...

36:25.310 --> 36:26.844
I tried.

36:26.879 --> 36:29.847
<i>[melancholy music]</i>

36:29.882 --> 36:36.888
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:50.736 --> 36:53.971
[engines thrumming]

36:55.340 --> 36:58.409
- Wyatt needs a doctor!
- Get a medic!

36:58.443 --> 37:01.412
<i>[indistinct over PA]</i>

37:01.446 --> 37:02.580
<i>Pressurization...</i>

37:02.614 --> 37:05.383
Thank you. You okay?

37:05.417 --> 37:07.518
[overlapping shouting in background]

37:12.457 --> 37:14.592
Who shot Lincoln?

37:14.626 --> 37:16.928
President Abraham
Lincoln was assassinated

37:16.962 --> 37:19.597
by a tall unknown
gunman using an unknown gun

37:19.631 --> 37:21.432
on April the 14th, 1865.

37:21.466 --> 37:24.001
But it's all changed.

37:24.036 --> 37:27.305
The gunman used to be John Wilkes Booth.

37:27.339 --> 37:28.906
Now it's Garcia Flynn.

37:28.941 --> 37:30.775
Well, the assassination was planned

37:30.809 --> 37:33.444
by John Wilkes Booth as
part of a larger conspiracy.

37:33.478 --> 37:35.012
Booth was hunted down and killed.

37:35.047 --> 37:36.414
The mysterious gunman

37:36.448 --> 37:38.649
also attempted to shoot General Grant,

37:38.684 --> 37:41.252
but he was saved by an obscure actress

37:41.286 --> 37:43.187
named Juliet Shakesman.

37:43.222 --> 37:46.357
Never seen again...

37:46.391 --> 37:50.661
though there is a high
school in Point Pleasant, Ohio,

37:50.696 --> 37:51.996
named after her.

37:52.030 --> 37:53.264
But what's it say about me?

37:53.298 --> 37:55.633
I saved Vice President Johnson.

37:55.667 --> 37:58.035
No, says he did.

37:58.070 --> 37:59.870
All that guy did was get shot.

37:59.905 --> 38:03.040
Well, besides the
fact that you let Flynn go,

38:03.075 --> 38:04.108
it's good work.

38:04.142 --> 38:06.377
But history changed.

38:06.411 --> 38:08.346
That's not how it's supposed to be.

38:08.380 --> 38:09.614
It's close enough.

38:09.648 --> 38:12.149
Is it?

38:12.184 --> 38:13.884
What if something changed somewhere

38:13.919 --> 38:15.453
because of what we did?

38:15.487 --> 38:17.121
Maybe someone else lost their sister.

38:17.155 --> 38:21.192
Flynn didn't destroy
America or the world.

38:21.226 --> 38:23.261
Take the win.

38:26.098 --> 38:27.732
Psst!

38:30.702 --> 38:32.536
Your father, Henry Wallace.

38:32.571 --> 38:34.038
Your mother, Carol Preston.

38:34.072 --> 38:36.974
Two children: you, Lucy, in 1983;

38:37.009 --> 38:40.344
and, according to you, your
sister was born in 1990.

38:40.379 --> 38:42.146
So how did the "Hindenburg" change it?

38:42.180 --> 38:43.848
Well, to get straight to the point,

38:43.882 --> 38:45.383
Henry never married Carol.

38:45.417 --> 38:47.518
You're saying my father
never married my mother?

38:47.552 --> 38:50.154
As far as I can tell,
they never even met.

38:50.188 --> 38:52.757
Instead, Henry married the granddaughter

38:52.791 --> 38:54.392
of Irene Doehner,

38:54.426 --> 38:56.196
a girl who should have
died in the "Hindenburg"

38:56.220 --> 38:57.771
but didn't.

38:57.796 --> 38:59.997
That explains why my mother
doesn't have lung cancer.

39:00.032 --> 39:01.699
Dad got her smoking.

39:01.733 --> 39:04.535
But since they never married,
she never smoked, no cancer.

39:04.569 --> 39:06.504
It also explains why Amy was never born.

39:06.538 --> 39:08.406
Right, because my parents never met.

39:08.440 --> 39:10.441
But they're still my parents.

39:10.475 --> 39:11.609
Keep going.

39:11.643 --> 39:13.177
So wait a minute.

39:13.211 --> 39:14.578
How was I born?

39:14.613 --> 39:17.415
You're almost there.

39:20.886 --> 39:23.854
Yeah, you got it.

39:23.889 --> 39:25.356
Carol's my mother,

39:25.390 --> 39:28.859
but Henry isn't my father and never was.

39:28.894 --> 39:32.963
My mother's been lying
to me my whole life.

39:32.998 --> 39:35.966
<i>[soft rock music]</i>

39:36.001 --> 39:43.007
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:44.476 --> 39:47.278
I'm not recording them anymore.

39:47.312 --> 39:49.814
I don't care who Rittenhouse is.

39:49.848 --> 39:52.049
Lucy and Wyatt trust me,

39:52.084 --> 39:53.784
and I am not spying on them.

39:53.819 --> 39:55.119
Rufus.

39:55.153 --> 39:56.954
Who took you out of West Chicago

39:56.988 --> 39:58.889
and sent you to MIT?

39:58.924 --> 40:03.561
Who bought your
mother a house and a car and...

40:03.595 --> 40:05.763
Oh, yes, that's
right... Brought you into

40:05.797 --> 40:10.067
one of the most important scientific
projects of all time?

40:10.102 --> 40:12.937
And I am grateful for all of that.

40:12.971 --> 40:15.473
Well, gratitude doesn't
repay your debt.

40:15.507 --> 40:18.476
Those recordings do.

40:18.510 --> 40:20.077
<i>♪ When people run in circles ♪</i>

40:20.112 --> 40:22.913
<i>♪ It's a very, very ♪</i>

40:22.948 --> 40:26.984
<i>♪ Mad world ♪</i>

40:27.018 --> 40:28.919
The doctor who did this sucks.

40:28.954 --> 40:31.355
<i>♪ Mad world ♪</i>

40:31.390 --> 40:33.624
It wasn't a doctor.

40:33.658 --> 40:34.859
I'll get you stitched up.

40:34.893 --> 40:36.660
We'll have you home by tonight.

40:38.964 --> 40:40.998
Who should we call to pick you up?

40:42.534 --> 40:43.701
I'll call a cab.

40:43.735 --> 40:50.608
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:50.642 --> 40:53.778
[overlapping chatter]

40:53.812 --> 40:56.113
- Hey, congrats.
- [applause]

40:56.148 --> 40:57.948
Wait, wait, wait, wait.

40:57.983 --> 41:00.818
Me first. Hold on.

41:00.852 --> 41:03.387
Well, you're late to
your own engagement party.

41:03.422 --> 41:06.991
My engagement party. Ha ha.

41:07.025 --> 41:09.560
The way you ran out
yesterday, and now this.

41:09.594 --> 41:11.996
And I'm not supposed to worry.

41:12.030 --> 41:13.397
I'm sorry.

41:13.432 --> 41:17.468
It's just been a little... hectic.

41:17.502 --> 41:18.969
I see.

41:19.004 --> 41:21.038
So did you help out your friend Amy?

41:23.041 --> 41:24.408
I'm still working on it.

41:24.443 --> 41:26.977
Well, please go freshen up

41:27.012 --> 41:29.213
and find your engagement ring.

41:29.247 --> 41:31.415
Mom.

41:31.450 --> 41:34.084
[sighs]

41:34.119 --> 41:36.687
I need to talk to you about something.

41:36.721 --> 41:38.055
About Dad.

41:38.089 --> 41:39.590
What are you not telling me?

41:39.624 --> 41:41.992
What? Are you serious right now?

41:42.027 --> 41:45.396
You bring this up on today, of all days?

41:46.431 --> 41:48.899
I need a drink.

41:48.934 --> 41:53.838
<i>♪ Mad world ♪</i>

41:53.872 --> 41:58.843
<i>♪ Mad world... ♪</i>

41:58.877 --> 42:00.711
Hello, beautiful.

42:02.481 --> 42:03.914
I missed you.

42:03.949 --> 42:10.554
<i>♪ Mad world ♪</i>

42:10.589 --> 42:13.224
Hello.

